</bibRefCitation>
), with morphology and color pattern resembling those of 
<taxonomicName box="[705,803,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis box="[705,803,220,244]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[818,930,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diligens">
<emphasis box="[818,930,220,244]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. diligens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[986,1143,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutissima">
<emphasis box="[986,1143,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. minutissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1269,1359,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lidiae">
<emphasis box="[1269,1359,220,244]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. lidiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[211,309,255,279]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis box="[211,309,255,279]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of its propodeum (gently convex around a narrow median groove) and its occipital carina, which does not reach the mandible insertion (
<figureCitation box="[650,721,290,313]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,257,1968,1990]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,1266,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[321,1266,1266,1947]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Protopolybia lidiae, sp. nov. 1. Head, frontal view; 2. Head, lateral view; 3. Scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, dorsal view; 4. Holotype specimen, lateral view. clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process; gm, genal margin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828519/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[735,750,290,313]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1276,1298]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,575,1255]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[321,1266,575,1255]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5. Protopolybia similis, head, lateral view; 6. P. diligens, head on frontal view; 7. P. diligens, scutellum, metanotum and propodeum on dorsal view; 8. P. minutissima, head on lateral view. gm, genal margin; clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828521/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">5</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[772,982,289,313]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lidiae">
<emphasis box="[772,982,289,313]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Protopolybia lidiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can also be confused with a variant of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diligens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. diligens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and although its clypeus is equally narrow (
<figureCitation box="[709,776,325,348]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,257,1968,1990]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,1266,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[321,1266,1266,1947]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Protopolybia lidiae, sp. nov. 1. Head, frontal view; 2. Head, lateral view; 3. Scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, dorsal view; 4. Holotype specimen, lateral view. clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process; gm, genal margin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828519/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[789,804,325,348]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1276,1298]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,575,1255]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[321,1266,575,1255]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5. Protopolybia similis, head, lateral view; 6. P. diligens, head on frontal view; 7. P. diligens, scutellum, metanotum and propodeum on dorsal view; 8. P. minutissima, head on lateral view. gm, genal margin; clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828521/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">6</figureCitation>
), the apex is different, being produced ventrally. Moreover, the metanotal process is wider with the apex more acute (
<figureCitation box="[793,865,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,257,1968,1990]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,1266,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[321,1266,1266,1947]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Protopolybia lidiae, sp. nov. 1. Head, frontal view; 2. Head, lateral view; 3. Scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, dorsal view; 4. Holotype specimen, lateral view. clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process; gm, genal margin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828519/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[880,895,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1276,1298]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,575,1255]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[321,1266,575,1255]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5. Protopolybia similis, head, lateral view; 6. P. diligens, head on frontal view; 7. P. diligens, scutellum, metanotum and propodeum on dorsal view; 8. P. minutissima, head on lateral view. gm, genal margin; clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828521/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">7</figureCitation>
), and it has no basal band on T2. The similarity between 
<taxonomicName box="[247,332,393,417]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lidiae">
<emphasis box="[247,332,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. lidiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[389,545,394,417]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutissima">
<emphasis box="[389,545,394,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. minutissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mainly in their color pattern and narrowing of the clypeus; however, 
<taxonomicName box="[1323,1411,393,417]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Protopolybia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lidiae">
<emphasis box="[1323,1411,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">P. lidiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly differentiated by the shape of its occipital carina, which does not reach the mandible insertion, but extends to about ¾ of the height of the gena (
<figureCitation box="[517,586,464,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,257,1968,1990]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,1266,1947]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[321,1266,1266,1947]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Protopolybia lidiae, sp. nov. 1. Head, frontal view; 2. Head, lateral view; 3. Scutellum, metanotum and propodeum, dorsal view; 4. Holotype specimen, lateral view. clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process; gm, genal margin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828519/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[598,613,464,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1276,1298]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,575,1255]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[321,1266,575,1255]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. 5. Protopolybia similis, head, lateral view; 6. P. diligens, head on frontal view; 7. P. diligens, scutellum, metanotum and propodeum on dorsal view; 8. P. minutissima, head on lateral view. gm, genal margin; clp, clypeus; mp, metanotal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/828521/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1238,498,521]" pageId="2" pageNumber="434" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,521]" box="[199,1238,498,521]" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,498,521]" pageId="2" pageNumber="434">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is in honor grandmother of first author (J.N. Santos), called Lídia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
